bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical Sketch
bioghist.p: Peter Štanský, born in New York in 1932, has had a long and distinguished career in the field of history. He received his first BA in History from Yale, and a few years later received his second BA in History from King’s College, Cambridge. Assuming he would eventually go into the practice of Law, he sent out but then withdrew applications to Harvard Law School, eventually earning his Ph.D. in History from Harvard. He taught at Harvard until 1968, when he joined the Stanford faculty. In 1974 Štanský became the holder of the endowed Frances and Charles Field Chair in History, and has been the chairman of Stanford's History Department for at least two terms.

Stanksy’s scholarly interests have been quite diverse during his time at Stanford University. He has authored or co-authored numerous books on British social and literary topics, such as The Unknown Orwell, The Road to Wigan Pier, Orwell: The Transformation, Ambitions and Strategies, and numerous other books on subjects including Winston Churchill, Victorian society, William Morris, and William Gladstone. Along with scholarly publications, Štanský has served on many Stanford committees and has been actively involved with the Stanford University Library collection development.

scopecontent.head: Description of the Collection
scopecontent.p: The first series of the Peter Štanský papers consists of three different sections, each representing a distinct academic activity Peter Štanský was involved with: his committee involvement, his publishing activities, and his library correspondence. His committee work ranged from Academic Senate, the Drama Department, the English Department, the Land and Building Committee, and the Foreign Campus Sub-Committee which was centered in Cliveden, England. The content of this section is predominantly minutes and correspondence with various committee members. The last of these committees, the Foreign Campus Sub-Committee, contains both the minutes of the meetings (boxes 2 and 3) and class lists and syllabi (box 4). Peter Štanský’s publishing activities constitute the second major portion of this collection. Along with the actual material dealing with the compilation of the text or book, this section also includes correspondence with the various publishers, such as Harcourt and Garland. The last two boxes of this collection (boxes 10 and 11) contain file cards with notes on his various publications. Finally, Peter Štanský was involved with Stanford’s library development, and included in his papers are his correspondence with the Stanford University Libraries from 1968-1980 (box 9).

An addition made in 2003 consists of two scrapbooks on Štanský's career, 1960-69. Accession 2015-167 contains materials from Štanský's early education, family letters, and research about Marina Alandra Vaizey. Accession 2017-060 contains research files for Štanský's book Edward Upward: Art and Life.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Peter Štanský subject files include manuscripts, research, correspondence, and reviews of some of Štanský’s publications dated 1974-2010. Subjects covered include C.R. Ashbee and H.W. Rolfe, Julian Bell, the Blitz, Bloomsbury, twentieth-century British artists, William Gladstone, William Morris, George Orwell, and Philip and Sybil Sassoon.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subject file contains research and correspondence about Julian Bell (1908-1937), an English poet and nephew of Virginia Woolf. Peter Štanský published two books about Julian Bell, including Journey to the Frontier: Julian Bell and John Cornford: Their lives and the 1930s with William Abrahams (1966), and Julian Bell: From Bloomsbury to the Spanish Civil War (2012).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subject file contains manuscripts and correspondence about the Blitz in London (1940-1941). It also contains book reviews for Peter Štanský’s publication The First Day of the Blitz (2007).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subject file contains manuscripts about Bloomsbury, as well as correspondence and book reviews for Peter Štanský’s publication On or About 1910: Early Bloomsbury and its Intimate World (1996).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subject file contains handwritten and typed notecards by Peter Štanský about twentieth-century British artists such as Henry Moore (1898-1986), Graham Sutherland (1903-1980), Paul Nash (1889-1946), and Benjamin Britten (1913-1976).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: In 1979 Peter Štanský’s book about the British politician William Ewart Gladstone (1809-1898) called Gladstone: A Progress in Politics was published. This subject file includes a manuscript of the book, as well as correspondence and book reviews related to the publication.

did.unittitle: Gladstone: A Progress in Politics manuscript
Gladstone: A Progress in Politics book reviews

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Peter Štanský researched and wrote two books about William Morris (1834-1896), an English artist and writer associated with the Arts and Crafts Movement. The book William Morris was published in 1983 and From William Morris to Sergeant Pepper in 1999. This research file contains some of Štanský’s manuscripts about Morris, along with correspondence and book reviews of From William Morris to Sergeant Pepper.

did.unittitle: From William Morris to Sergeant Pepper book reviews

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Peter Štanský researched and presented papers on George Orwell (1903-1950) throughout his career as a professor and historian. This subject file includes Štanský’s manuscripts, correspondence, and research related to George Orwell.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Two members of the prominent Sassoon family, Philip Sassoon (1888-1939) and his sister Sybil Sassoon (1894-1989) became the subject of one of his Peter Štanský’s many books. Sassoon: The Worlds of Philip and Sybil was published in 2003. This subject file contains book reviews of this publication, along with Štanský’s manuscripts, research, and correspondence related to the Sassoon family.
